As of July 1, 2018, U.S. Census Bureau estimates placed Leesburg's population at 53,917. The [2010 census](/2010_United_States_Census) recorded 42,616 residents, comprising 14,441 households and 10,522 families, resulting in a population density of 3,673 inhabitants per square mile (1,418/km 2 ). The housing situation included 15,119 units, with an average density of 1,220.2 per square mile (471.1/km 2 ).

The racial composition of Leesburg, according to the 2010 census, was as follows: 71.1% [White](/White_(U.S._Census)), 9.5% [African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)), 0.4% [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)), 7.1% [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._Census)), 0.0% [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_(U.S._Census)), 7.5% identified with other races, and 4.3% reported belonging to two or more races. [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) individuals constituted 17.4% of the population.

Household demographics revealed that 44.4% of households included children under 18. [Married couples](/Marriage) living together accounted for 57.8% of households, while 10.5% were headed by a female with no husband present. Non-family households made up 27.1% of the total. Individuals living alone represented 21.1% of households, with 4.9% of those individuals being 65 years or older. The average household size was 2.93, and the average family size was 3.42.

The age distribution showed 30.7% of the population under 18, 5.5% between 18 and 24, 32.9% from 25 to 44, 23.4% from 45 to 64, and 6.1% aged 65 and over. The median age was 33.3 years. The male-to-female ratio was 95.7 males per 100 females, and for those aged 18 and over, it was 93.6 males per 100 females.

Economic indicators from 2010 showed a median household income of $68,861 and a median family income of $78,111. By 2007, these figures had reportedly risen to $87,346 and $105,260, respectively. The median income for males was $51,267, contrasted with $35,717 for females. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for Leesburg was $30,116. Approximately 2.4% of families and 3.6% of the population lived below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line), with figures of 3.8% for those under 18 and 8.2% for those 65 and older.

#### Education

Leesburg is served by the [Loudoun County Public Schools](/Loudoun_County_Public_Schools) district, which operates four public high schools: [Loudoun County High School](/Loudoun_County_High_School), [Heritage High School](/Heritage_High_School_(Leesburg,_Virginia)), [Tuscarora High School](/Tuscarora_High_School_(Virginia)), and [Riverside High School](/Riverside_High_School_(Loudoun_County,_Virginia)).

The town also hosts several private educational institutions, including Providence Academy (K–8, non-denominational Christian), Leesburg Christian School (K–12, non-denominational Christian), and the [Loudoun Country Day School](/Loudoun_Country_Day_School) (pre-K–8).

#### Public Services

Fire protection in Leesburg is provided by the Leesburg Volunteer Fire Company. Emergency medical and rescue services are handled by the Loudoun County Volunteer Rescue Squad. Both organizations operate as volunteer entities, supplemented by staff from the Loudoun County Department of Fire, Rescue and Emergency Management. The fire company's origins trace back to 1803, while the rescue squad was established in 1952.

Leesburg maintains its own town police department, the Leesburg Police Department (LPD), which is distinct from the [Loudoun County Sheriff's Office](/Loudoun_County_Sheriff%27s_Office). The LPD, formed in 1758, is authorized to employ 90 sworn officers and provides round-the-clock patrol, criminal investigation, traffic control, and specialized operations within the town. The Loudoun County Sheriff's Office is the primary law enforcement agency for the county and provides security for the courthouse located in Leesburg.

#### Media

The [Loudoun Times-Mirror](/Loudoun_Times-Mirror) is a weekly newspaper based in Leesburg, serving the broader [Loudoun County, Virginia](/Loudoun_County,_Virginia). Local radio broadcasting ceased with the shutdown of WAGE (now [WTSD](/WTSD_(AM))) in 2007. Leesburg falls within the [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.) media market, receiving coverage from its major television and radio stations. Broadcasts from [Baltimore](/Baltimore), [Frederick, Maryland](/Frederick,_Maryland), and [Winchester, Virginia](/Winchester,_Virginia) are also readily accessible.

#### Transportation

Key transportation routes serving Leesburg include [U.S. Route 15](/U.S._Route_15_in_Virginia), [Virginia State Route 7](/Virginia_State_Route_7), and [Virginia State Route 267](/Virginia_State_Route_267).

US 15 enters Leesburg from the southwest, proceeding along King Street before merging with the Leesburg Bypass to circumnavigate the southeastern edge of the downtown area. It then rejoins King Street as it exits the bypass to the northeast, en route to Maryland. The former alignment of US 15 is now designated as [U.S. Route 15 Business](/U.S._Route_15_Business_(Leesburg,_Virginia)). Via US 15, travelers can reach [Warrenton, Virginia](/Warrenton,_Virginia) (34 miles southwest) and [Frederick, Maryland](/Frederick,_Maryland) (25 miles northeast).

SR 7 enters Leesburg from the west on Market Street, quickly joining the Leesburg Bypass to pass southwest of the town center. It then follows Market Street again as it departs the bypass southeast of downtown. The historical alignment of SR 7 is now [Virginia State Route 7 Business](/Virginia_State_Route_7). SR 7 provides access 37 miles west to [Winchester, Virginia](/Winchester,_Virginia) and 35 miles southeast to [Alexandria, Virginia](/Alexandria,_Virginia).

SR 267, the [Dulles Greenway](/Dulles_Greenway), enters Leesburg from the south and terminates at the junction with the Leesburg Bypass (US 15 and SR 7). SR 267 functions as a high-speed, tolled bypass for SR 7 in the southeastern part of Leesburg.

Public transportation is provided by [Loudoun County Transit](/Loudoun_County_Transit), offering commuter routes to [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.) and a connector service to [Purcellville, Virginia](/Purcellville,_Virginia).

The [Washington and Old Dominion Railroad](/Washington_and_Old_Dominion_Railroad) once served Leesburg. Its former right-of-way has been converted into the [Washington and Old Dominion Railroad Regional Park](/Washington_and_Old_Dominion_Railroad_Regional_Park), a popular rail trail.

#### Business and Industry

Leesburg operates the [Leesburg Executive Airport](/Leesburg_Executive_Airport) at Godfrey Field, which caters to Loudoun County's private and corporate aviation needs. Identified as a reliever airport for Dulles International, the airport contributes approximately $78 million annually to the local economy, according to a 2011 study by the Virginia Department of Aviation. As of 2005, it was home to over 240 aircraft and handled 20–30 jet operations daily. The airport was established in 1963, replacing the original Leesburg airport, which entertainer Arthur Godfrey affectionately called "The Old Cow Pasture" on his radio show. Godfrey, who owned the Beacon Hill Estate west of Leesburg by the early 1950s, used a [DC-3](/Douglas_DC-3) to commute to New York City. The aircraft's power and noise led Godfrey to fund the construction of a new, larger airport by selling the original field. Originally named Godfrey Field, it is now known as [Leesburg Executive Airport](/Leesburg_Executive_Airport) at Godfrey Field.

The National Conference Center, constructed by [Xerox](/Xerox) Corporation in the 1970s, is also located near Leesburg. This facility serves as a venue for meetings and conferences for both government agencies and private businesses. It comprises a complex network of underground buildings, with one section currently housing the headquarters of [Civilian Police International](/Civilian_Police_International), a government sub-contractor.

Market Station, situated in the southeastern part of Leesburg's Historic District, occupies seven restored historic structures. These include a [railroad](/Railroad) freight station, a stationmaster's house, a [log house](/Log_home), two [barns](/Barn), and two [gristmills](/Gristmill). The complex now houses various high-tech and legal offices, retail shops, and [restaurants](/Restaurant). A plaza on the east side features structures painted in the distinctive yellow and green colors of the former [Washington and Old Dominion Railroad](/Washington_and_Old_Dominion_Railroad), which served the town until 1968.

The operations of [Iridium Communications Inc.](/Iridium_Communications) (formerly Iridium Satellite LLC), a satellite communications company, are managed from a nondescript office building in Leesburg.

