#### Recreational Facilities and Events

##### Parks

*   **Ida Lee Park**: Located on the north side of Leesburg, this park was established in 1986 following the donation of Greenwood Farm to the town by William F. Rust Jr. and his wife, Margaret Dole Rust. The 141-acre (57 ha) farm was bequeathed for the perpetual use as Ida Lee Park. The Rusts requested the park be named in memory of Ida Lee Rust, Mr. Rust's grandmother, to honor the historical connection between the [Lee family](/Lee_family) of Virginia and Leesburg. Ida Lee Rust was the daughter of Edmund Jennings Lee and a first cousin of Robert E. Lee. She spent her married life at "Rockland," the Rust family home near Leesburg, and later resided in a house built by her sons at 113 East Cornwall Street in Leesburg. The Rusts also donated three acres adjacent to the park for the Rust Library. In 1991, they contributed $50,000 for the construction of the William J. Cox Pavilion at Ida Lee Park, a public picnic area featuring a pavilion and playground.

*   **[Morven Park](/Morven_Park)**: This 1,000-acre (400 ha) historic [estate](/Estate_(house)) functions as a significant horse park. Its grounds include the Morven Park Mansion, the [Winmill](/Viola_Townsend_Winmill) Carriage Museum, formal gardens, extensive hiking and riding trails, and athletic fields. The park also houses the Museum of Hounds and Hunting of North America, showcasing art, artifacts, and memorabilia related to the sport of [foxhunting](/Foxhunting).

*   **[Washington & Old Dominion Railroad Trail](/Washington_%26_Old_Dominion_Railroad_Regional_Park)**: This 45-mile-long (72 km) [rail trail](/Rail_trail), constructed by the [Northern Virginia Regional Park Authority](/Northern_Virginia_Regional_Park_Authority) on the former [W&OD RR](/Washington_and_Old_Dominion_Railroad) [right-of-way](/Right-of-way_(transportation)), offers a recreational route for [hikers](/Hiking), [bikers](/Bicycle), and [joggers](/Jogging) through and around Leesburg.

*   **Red Rocks Wilderness Overlook Regional Park**: Situated east of Leesburg along the [Potomac River](/Potomac_River), this 67-acre (27 ha) park, managed by the NVRPA, features woodlands and over two miles of trails leading to overlooks on the river bluffs. Frances Speek donated the land to the NVRPA in 1978. The park's ruins date back to 1869 and were part of the estate of industrialist Charles R. Paxton, known for constructing the Victorian mansion [Carlheim](/Carlheim).

*   **The Rust Manor House and Nature Sanctuary**: Located near the western edge of Leesburg at the base of [Catoctin Mountain](/Catoctin_Mountain), this sanctuary comprises a [mansion](/Mansion) and a [nature reserve](/Nature_reserve) managed by the [Audubon Naturalist Society of the Central Atlantic States, Inc.](/Audubon_Naturalist_Society).

##### Events

*   **Leesburg Flower and Garden Festival**: Held annually in April within the Historic District, this festival features garden displays, vendors, and entertainment.

*   **[Fourth of July](/Independence_Day_(United_States)) Celebration**: Festivities typically include a morning parade, a festival at Ida Lee Park, and evening fireworks.

*   **Classic Car Show**: This annual event, held on the first Saturday in June, showcases numerous classic cars and hot rods in downtown Leesburg, accompanied by music and food. Proceeds benefit the Graphic Arts and Auto Body programs at C.S. Monroe Technology Center.

*   **Leesburg AirShow**: Occurring annually on the last Saturday in September, this event features parachute jumpers, aerobatic performances, warbirds, model aircraft, military vehicles, and classic cars displayed on the airport ramp, along with music and food.

*   **[Halloween](/Halloween) [Parade](/Parade)**: Claimed to be one of the longest-running Halloween parades in the nation, it includes marching bands from local high schools, floats from local businesses, Scout troops, and families. Participants often distribute [candy](/Candy) to spectators.

*   **Santa Rides**: Since 1988, members of the Leesburg Volunteer Fire Company have decorated a fire apparatus with Christmas lights, carrying Santa, Rudolph, and Frosty. This event, observed by an estimated 30,000 people annually, brings holiday cheer to the town.

#### Notable People

This section requires citations for its claims. Please help improve it by adding reliable sources.

*   **[Jonathan Allen](/Jonathan_Allen)**: Professional football player for the [Washington Commanders](/Washington_Commanders), raised in Leesburg and attended [Stone Bridge High School](/Stone_Bridge_High_School) in [Ashburn, Virginia](/Ashburn,_Virginia).

*   **[Russell Baker](/Russell_Baker)**: Author.

*   **[Thomas Balch](/Thomas_Balch_(historian))**: Historian, born in Leesburg.

*   **[Joe Bauserman](/Joe_Bauserman)**: Former minor league baseball and college football player, briefly with the [Ohio State Buckeyes](/Ohio_State_Buckeyes_football), born in Leesburg.

*   **[Calle Brown](/Calle_Brown)**: Soccer player.

*   **[Westmoreland Davis](/Westmoreland_Davis)**: 48th [governor of Virginia](/Governor_of_Virginia).

*   **[James Dickey](/James_Dickey)**: Author, wrote his novel *Deliverance* while residing at Glenfiddich House from 1966 to 1968.

*   **[Arthur Godfrey](/Arthur_Godfrey)**: Entertainer, resided in Leesburg. The municipal airport, Godfrey Field, is named in his honor.

*   **[Mark Herring](/Mark_Herring)**: [Attorney General of Virginia](/Attorney_General_of_Virginia).

*   **[Fred Hetzel](/Fred_Hetzel)**: Former professional basketball player.

*   **[Billy Hurley III](/Billy_Hurley_III)**: [PGA Tour](/PGA_Tour) golfer.

*   **[Lyndon LaRouche](/Lyndon_LaRouche)**: Political activist, lived near Leesburg from 1983 until his imprisonment in 1989.

*   **[George C. Marshall](/George_C._Marshall)**: American Chief of Staff and five-star general during [World War II](/World_War_II), [Secretary of State](/United_States_Secretary_of_State), and architect of the [Marshall Plan](/Marshall_Plan). Resided at [Dodona Manor](/Dodona_Manor).

*   **[Roland Martin](/Roland_Martin_(journalist))**: Journalist and commentator.

*   **[Stevens T. Mason](/Stevens_T._Mason)**: Politician and the first [governor of Michigan](/Governor_of_Michigan).

*   **[Lewis Nixon](/Lewis_Nixon_(naval_architect))**: U.S. naval architect and former leader of [Tammany Hall](/Tammany_Hall), born in Leesburg.

*   **[Joseph B. Payne](/Joseph_B._Payne)**: (Died 1968) Member of the Maryland House of Delegates.

*   **[Jeremy Roach](/Jeremy_Roach)**: Basketball player for the [Duke Blue Devils](/Duke_Blue_Devils).

*   **[Clara Schwartz](/Murder_of_Robert_Schwartz)**: Convicted murderer.

*   **[Mohamad Anas Haitham Soueid](/Mohamad_Anas_Haitham_Soueid)**: Syrian-born naturalized U.S. citizen indicted on espionage-related charges in October 2011.

*   **[Tiffany Taylor](/Tiffany_Taylor_(model))**: Playmate of the Month for November 1998.

*   **[John Tolbert, Jr.](/John_Tolbert)**: Local education activist and politician.

*   **[Will Toledo](/Will_Toledo)**: Lead singer, songwriter, and musician of the indie rock band [Car Seat Headrest](/Car_Seat_Headrest); born and raised in Leesburg.

*   **[Jennifer Wexton](/Jennifer_Wexton)**: (Born 1968) Former [U.S. representative](/U.S._House_of_Representatives), [Virginia state senator](/Senate_of_Virginia), and prosecutor.

*   **[Joseph Winters](/Joseph_Winters)**: (1816–1916) [African-American](/African-American) [abolitionist](/Abolitionism_in_the_United_States).

*   The fictional character **[Supergirl](/Supergirl)** was stated to be born in Leesburg.

